snippet.textDisplay: It's genuinely painful to think of how bad doctor experiences make it so much harder on not just patients, but also the medical community as a whole. As a black woman, I am often confronted with the harsh truth that the color of my skin and my gender shape the way I am treated within the healthcare system.
There have been times when I have walked into doctors' offices with obvious signs that I needed medical attention, only to be met with skepticism and dismissal. The subtle eye rolls, the condescending tones, and the implicit questioning of my pain have become all too familiar. My pleas for help have often been met with apathy or a rushed diagnosis without thorough examination. It is as though my voice is muted, my concerns diminished, and my experiences invalidated. The emotional toll of these encounters is immense, disheartening and demoralizing.

snippet.textDisplay: Doctors never believe me because I'm female and autistic. When I was 14 I started gaining weight and my menstrual cycle was really messed up (for the first two years I figured it was normal because my mom says for the first two years it can be irregular). I had always been underweight due to ARFID (an eating disorder) and suddenly gaining weight was really weird for me. I asked doctors (psychiatrist mostly because of monthly appts where I was weighed) and they just said "oh, it's normal, maybe you're just less active because you're out of school." or "You're just getting older and your metabolism is slowing." alright, I thought. It was only five pounds. Then next month it was another five. Then it was seven. Ten. Fifteen. I kept gaining weight and doctors kept saying I was just getting fat because the eating disorder had restricted my diet to mostly carbs. But I didnt eat that much. Not enough to explain it. Eventually I gained 30 pounds in two months and finally managed to convince someone that my antidepressants were making me gain weight. I stopped them, and stop gaining weight, but even with a more active lifestyle and diet improvements I couldn't lose any weight. From age 14 to age 18 I gained 75lbs without ever getting taller. And I couldnt lose it. And even after mentioning the issues and my suspicion of what I had to doctors for 4 years prior, and my issues with my menstrual cycle, and my family history of it, it took me until I was 19 YEARS OLD for them to diagnose me with PCOS (polycystic ovarian syndrome). Doctors never believed me.

snippet.textDisplay: I have been re-watching a lot of these videos this weekend in my down time, and I gotta say, this one hits the closest to home. I've been very fortunate and lucky to have one hell of a mom and good doctors. I've always been aware of how blessed I am. I've had a good gyno my whole life, the woman who delivered me actually, lol, but even I've had a bad experience. My right hip was almost dislocating from the socket when I was 9.

Nine.

I went to my pediatrician to have it checked out. I explained that I could do it with a certain motion intentionally. And it would sometimes just happen when I fell, stepped weird, when my ankle crippled, when I adjusted my leg while sitting, anytime.

He then had me lay down, did the incredibly painful motion more than thirty times, and promptly looked me dead in my eye and said
"That's your knee. They do that sometimes. You're fine."

...my mom had looked at the inside of my thigh and hip joint and could SEE THE BONE MOVING WRONG and he did too.
Nope. My knee.
He also ignored my shoulder which crunched and ground and rolled painfully.

I continued to have issues and pain for years, and finally got a diagnosis when I was 16. Turns out I have hyper mobility joint syndrome.

So my feet having a muscle pull? Part of that due to weak Achilles.
My ankles literally giving out and crippling to a 90 degree angle and making me fall down stairs? That was a symptom.
My shoulder? Symptom
My hip? Symptom.
My fingers bending weird? Symptom.

It was the first time any doctor had actually listened to me about the issue, and it was so much better because I went to the Shriner's Children's Hospital and the nurse who treated me also has hyper mobility. For the first time I felt heard about my bones and the pain and the humiliation of always having issues, of being 16 and not being able to walk right. I actually cried because I was so emotional about being heard.

So yeah. Mine is a lot less severe, more of an annoyance, but it can happen to anyone. Be supportive of one another.

I wish everyone luck in finding a good doctor, especially people of color and women

I'm 30 years old, I frickin know what period cramps feel like. So I wound up sitting there for 8 hours, letting them run their tests, all the while I'm exploding with pain. GUESS WHOSE APPENDIX WAS BURSTING AND I WOUND UP NEEDING EMERGENCY SURGERY TO HAVE IT REMOVED. So annoying the way these assholes feel like they can play with our lives. I understand some people exaggerate but healthcare is so damn expensive, I wouldn't be there if it wasn't absolutely serious. I love that John brought attention to this but seeing as how this came out in 2019 and I'm writing this in 2022, I'm not sure much has changed.

snippet.textDisplay: In research, we talk about this as the difference between internal validity (does the drug we make work) and external validity (does the drug work for all people in the "real world"). 95% of funding goes to study internal validity, just to see if the drug works in labs. Because of this, doctors want to account for everything. If they could, they would clone one guy a million times and test all their drugs on him one at a time. The problem is, knowing a drug works only in one lab one time isn't exactly useful. It's lead some to argue that granting agencies should require diverse participants because if your drug only works on middle class white men between the ages of 18-24 in the 1960s, maybe your drug shouldn't be said to actually work.

I am a 63 year old single female who regularly experiences shockingly horrible health care (dismissive attitudes from doctors, rushing me, etc. I am misdiagnosed more often than not as a result. A few years ago, a doctor wanted to do a needle biopsy on a nodule on my thyroid. I refused after finding a study that proves fine needle biopsies can seed cancer cells elsewhere in the body as well as along the needle track. The specialist said this isn't true (but ncbi.nml.nih.gov says it is in an online article titled 'Risk of tumor cell seeding through biopsy and aspiration cytology"....e.g. in the study, 335 out of 353 BREAST cancers spread as a result of needle biopsies, and there was ZERO spread of the cancer for an additional 353 women who had the tumor removed WITHOUT first having a needle biopsy done!!!

When I said that the nodule has all the cancer markers so just take it out, my PCP said that this is not how it is done. (so...it is still in my neck) Here is where I believe the bias comes into play: I recently discovered that needle biopsies are not done on testis and the following is why (according to the American Cancer Society's website):

'Surgery (is used) to diagnose testicular cancer.'
' A biopsy is rarely done for a testicular tumor because¬†it might risk spreading the cancer.'
PLEASE EVERYONE:
SPREAD THE WORD ABOUT THE VERY REAL POTENTIAL DANGER OF NEEDLE BIOPSIES (esp for breasts)and try to stay safe and healthy while still doing what is good and right.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have post-concussion syndrome, a result from a traumatic brain injury, and I've had a constant headache since 2014. When my pain management doctor stopped prescribing opioids to me because he wasn't "comfortable" prescribing it any longer. He told me he tried everything, but indomethacin was his last idea.

Indomethacin is a VERY strong NSAID, and the pain management doctor instructed me to "take as needed". My pain is constant. He knew that. Like, my average days are about a six on the pain scale and even on those average days, I will *always* get random ice-pick headaches (it feels and looks like I'm being hit in the head with an invisible baseball bat) that are always accompanied by a tic that makes my head jerk away from the stabbing feeling.

That's my average. And that's not including the chronic migraines I had about ten times a month.

I ended up getting an ulcer that was literally half the size of my stomach and the doctors were worried that I could have fucking cancer (I don't, and I'm fine now).

When I was lying on the floor waiting for an ambulance because I couldn't lift my head anymore, my mom said that I was literally as white as a sheet of paper. The paramedics had a hard time finding a vein for an IV (by the end of my hospital stay I had, in total, about seven huge bruises on my hands and arms from needing a new IV so often).

I needed four pints of blood. I nearly bled to death internally because, to quote google: "indomethacin may cause ulcers, bleeding, or holes in the stomach or intestine. These problems may develop at any time during treatment, may happen without warning symptoms, and may cause death."

So, yeah. I could function perfectly fine with a constant headache that was eased a bit with Tylenol-3 stopping *any* of the ice-pick headaches that sometimes incapacitate me. And because my pain management doctor was "not comfortable" about continuing to prescribe it to me, he gave me a prescription for an NSAID that my primary care doctor later told me should never have been prescribed to me at all because of the nature of my traumatic brain injury and chronic migraine.

If I'd been able to get delta-8 vape cartridges four years ago, I would have been spared internal bleeding.

Thank goodness they developed delta-8 (the Banana Runtz strain is my preference), because vaping this shit helps way more than the Tylenol-3 at preventing migraines‚Äîwhich was why I had to get sumatriptan injectors on top of the Tylenol-3. Vaping delta-8 helps ease my regular headache and prevents migraines.

My point is, because my pain management doctor wasn't "comfortable" keeping me on a medication that was helping me function, he put me on an NSAID that nearly killed me.

Side note: my traumatic brain injury straight up destroyed the part of my brain that keeps me from oversharing. Hence the five hundred word detailed info dump on my experience with a shitty pain management doctor.
